# Validation

Validation checks that the system satisfies the requirements of the analysis
chapter. The strategy follows directly from the architecture: because the design
pushed all the hard logic into a **pure, deterministic domain** (NFR1, NFR4),
the bulk of the system can be tested automatically with no GUI, socket, or clock;
the parts that genuinely depend on the outside world (rendering, native WebRTC,
two-machine play) are validated manually.

## Automatic Testing

The automated suite is roughly **85 Kotest cases** plus two native WebRTC
harnesses. It is organized in four tiers.

### Unit tests — domain logic

Each domain system is exercised in isolation as a pure function. These are the
acceptance tests for the in-match functional requirements (FR4–FR6).

| Spec | Cases | Covers | Requirement |
| ---- | ----- | ------ | ----------- |
| `InputSystemSpec` | 13 | Horizontal movement, grounded jump (no double jump), diagonal/opposing input, hitstun blocks input | FR4, FR6 |
| `PlayerStateSpec` | 12 | IDLE / WALKING / JUMPING / ATTACKING / HITSTUN transitions, floor reset | FR4, FR6 |
| `PhysicsSystemSpec` | 9 | Gravity, terminal velocity, floor collision, stage-bound clamping, knockback | FR4, FR6 |
| `AttackSystemSpec` | 6 | Frame advance, STARTUP → ACTIVE → RECOVERY, attack expiry | FR4 |
| `CrouchSpec` / `FacingSpec` | 7 / 5 | Crouch state, facing the opponent | FR4 |
| `HitDetectionSystemSpec` | 6 | No hit in STARTUP/RECOVERY, hit in ACTIVE, out-of-range miss, no double hit | FR5 |
| `RectangleSpec` | 3 | AABB overlap, separation, edge/corner non-overlap | FR5 |
| `HealthSpec` | 1 | Damage reduces HP, clamped at zero | FR5 |

### Determinism regression — the cross-peer guarantee

Rollback only works if both machines compute bit-identical results from identical
inputs. Two specs encode that guarantee *locally*, so it is checked on every
build rather than only when two machines are connected (NFR1, FR8).

- **`DeterminismSpec`** (2) runs `GameLogic.step` twice over fixed 600- and
  3600-frame scripted input sequences and asserts per-frame state matches
  exactly. Any accidental non-determinism (an `Instant.now()`, a `Math.random`,
  an unordered `HashSet`) fails the build.
- **`WorldHashSpec`** (6) checks the canonical hash used for desync detection:
  determinism, sensitivity to single-ULP position / frame / health changes,
  and insensitivity to map insertion order.

### Integration — netcode under simulated latency

`RollbackServiceSpec` (5) is the key interaction test. It builds a fake
`DelayedRemote` transport that runs the *peer's* identical `RollbackService` and
adds configurable network delay, then asserts:

| Property | What it proves | Requirement |
| -------- | -------------- | ----------- |
| Zero-delay correctness | With no delay, output equals a zero-latency reference run | FR8 |
| Convergence under delay | Sweeping delay ∈ {1,2,4,6}, the run still reaches identical final state after many rewinds | FR8, NFR3 |
| Stalls when ahead | A peer pinned behind causes exactly `syncThreshold + 1` advances then stalls | NFR3 |
| Bounded advantage | Against a constant deficit, the frame gap stays bounded (no unbounded drift) | FR8 |
| Desync detection | A disagreeing peer hash fires exactly one `onDesync`; a matching one fires none | FR8 |

`NetworkAdapterSpec` (5) covers the transport plumbing: `peerFrame()` tracks the
maximum reported frame and never regresses on out-of-order delivery, and
committed-hash draining dedupes by frame. `JsonCharacterRepositorySpec` (5)
covers loading the character/attack tables, and `MainTest` (2) covers the
composition root wiring.

### Native and end-to-end

The C++ WebRTC layer is validated by two harnesses under `channel/test/`:
`protocol_test.cpp` and `local_test.cpp` each create **two peers in one process**,
pass SDP and ICE directly between them (no signaling server), open the data
channel, and exchange packets — confirming the bridge and the 36-byte wire format
end-to-end without a network. Full end-to-end play (two JVM instances over
loopback WebRTC, then two physical machines) is exercised manually.

### How to run

```bash
./gradlew test                       # all Kotest specs + quality gates
./gradlew test --tests "*DeterminismSpec"
./gradlew test --tests "*RollbackServiceSpec"
cd channel && cmake --build build    # then run build/.../local_test
```

### Quality gates

Every `./gradlew build` must pass four gates, all treated as blocking: **detekt**
(static analysis), **ktlint** (formatting), `compileKotlin` with
`allWarningsAsErrors`, and the full **test** suite. These run in CI on GitHub
Actions, so a regression cannot merge. Corner cases are covered where they are
deterministic — dropped packets (convergence-under-delay), out-of-order packets
(`peerFrame` monotonicity), clock drift (bounded-advantage), and divergence
(desync detection).

## Acceptance Test

Several requirements cannot be checked by a pure function because they depend on
real rendering, the native WebRTC stack, the live services, or two separate
machines. These were validated by **manual acceptance testing**, following each
requirement's acceptance criterion.

| Requirement | Manual check | Why not automated |
| ----------- | ------------ | ----------------- |
| FR1 — register / login | Register and log in against the running auth service; reuse and bad credentials rejected | The Go services have no unit suite; exercised against the live service |
| FR2 — matchmaking | Launch three clients; first two pair, third waits for a fourth | Requires multiple live clients and the signaling server |
| FR3 — P2P / NAT traversal | Two machines behind different routers connect and play | Depends on real NATs and a public STUN server |
| FR6 — hitstun / knockback | Land a hit; opponent slides back and cannot act for ~12 frames | Underlying logic is unit-tested; the *feel* is verified visually |
| FR7 — rounds / timer | Timer counts 99 → 0, round ends, best-of decides the match | No `GameRules` spec yet; verified by playing |
| FR9 — visual feedback | Resize the window; the stage scales proportionally; hitboxes show only when active | Rendering correctness is inherently visual |
| FR10 — interactive wait / cancel | Practice loop stays responsive while queued; *Cancel* returns to the menu | Depends on the GUI event loop |

The main automation gaps — unit tests for the Go services and a `GameRules` round
spec — are noted in the future-works chapter rather than hidden.
